The Theoretical Perspectives of Social Gerontology and Their Application of Welfare Policy
Su-Ke Ye  

Assistant Professor, Department of Sociology, Soochow University 
�@�@�@A number of social theories have been developed to explain the aging process. Disengagement theory suggests that society and the elderly mutually sever many of their relationships, whereas activity theory argues that elderly people remain socially active determines the quality of their lives in old age. Subculture theory sees the elderly as a distinct subculture, while continuity theory holds that people adapt best to age role changes when they able to continue roles and activities that they experienced and found rewarding earlier in life. Conflict theory assumes that the elderly places in a subordinate social status due to loss of power, and exchange theory explain that the decreased power of the elderly is a result of their devaluation as partners in social exchange.   

�@�@These theories are supplementary in explaining the actual life of the elderly. Although they overlap, each has its unique emphasis. Older people face so many problems that demand immediate solutions, research in the field of social gerontology thus has often been applied rather than purely theoretical. In other words, researchers have invested much of their time in seeking effective social solution, often neglecting the broader theoretical questions.   

�@�@The main purpose of this article is intending to make a sketchy review on social theories of aging and some issues emerged from their theoretical arguments. It is argued that the twenty-first century will usher in changing demographics, and the over-65 population will increase dramatically throughout the world. This graying trend promises to have dramatic political, economic and social impact, and it will affect virtually all aspects of Taiwanese society. Also, this article show that different models of social service and welfare policies for the elderly have been implemented to cope with many problems and difficulties encountered in the aging process in the future.  

�@Key Words: social gerontology, aging society, the social structure of old age, social theories of aging, 

social welfare policy

 





